### Workflow tools

* `put_test_raw(test_source)` -- overwrite the working buffer with new
  source.
* `get_test()` -- read the current buffer.
* `forge_test(seed=None)` -- run `forge test` on your current buffer.
  Pass `seed="..."` to replay a prior fuzz/invariant counterexample
  (see the fuzz section below). Omit `seed` for a normal run; only a
  fully-green *unseeded* run stamps the publish gate -- seeded runs
  never stamp, even when clean.
* `record_skip(property_title, reason)` /
  `unskip_property(property_title)` -- declare a property unformalizable
  (with justification). Skipped properties don't need a test_ function
  and must NOT appear in the publish-time property→test mapping.
* `expect_test_failure(test_name, reason)` /
  `expect_test_passage(test_name)` -- mark/unmark a test as expected to
  fail. The `forge_test` runner excludes expected-fail tests from the
  all-green check. Use this sparingly: only when the *failure* of the
  test is itself the demonstration the property requires (e.g., proving
  an attack vector is reachable). For routine "this should revert"
  assertions, prefer `vm.expectRevert(...)` inline.
* `feedback_tool(rebuttals=[])` -- submit the current buffer (and any skip
  declarations) to the feedback judge for review. A judge acceptance
  stamps the publish gate; like the `forge_test` stamp, it is invalidated
  by any subsequent `put_test_raw` or skip change.
* `result(commentary, property_tests)` -- publish. Rejected unless BOTH
  `forge_test` and the feedback judge have stamped the current buffer
  (i.e., a green unseeded run and a judge acceptance after your most
  recent `put_test_raw`). `property_tests` is checked against the tests
  forge actually ran: every non-skipped property must be demonstrated by
  ≥1 test that ran, and every test that ran must be tied back to one of
  the batch's properties.
* `give_up(reason)` -- last-resort exit.

## Test naming

Foundry's runner picks tests up by **prefix**. Use these prefixes exactly:

* **Unit tests** must begin with `test_...`. The function must be `public`
  and take no arguments.
* **Fuzz tests** must begin with `testFuzz_...`. The function takes one or
  more arguments; foundry generates random values for each on every run.
* **Invariant tests** must begin with `invariant_...`. The function is
  `public view`, takes no arguments, and is called by the invariant
  runner after every step in a randomly generated call sequence.

Within those three prefixes, use these consistent descriptive suffixes:

* `test_RevertWhen_<StateOrPrecondition>(...)` -- a unit test that asserts
  the call reverts when some state-based precondition holds. Use
  `vm.expectRevert(...)` inline; the suffix is documentation, not magic.
* `test_RevertIf_<RuntimeCondition>(...)` -- same shape, but the trigger
  is a runtime condition on arguments rather than persistent state.
* `test_WhenCalledBy_<Role>(...)` -- a unit test scoped to a specific
  `msg.sender` role (use `vm.prank(...)`).
* `testFuzz_RevertWhen_<...>` / `testFuzz_<Property>(...)` -- same suffix
  conventions, just with fuzzed inputs.
* `invariant_<HumanReadableProperty>(...)` -- e.g.
  `invariant_TotalSupplyMatchesDeposits`.

The test function identifier appears verbatim in failure reports, so
err on the side of long-and-specific.

## Authoring guidance

* Use `setUp()` for shared deployment and configuration; instantiate
  contracts under test in `setUp()`, not in individual tests. `setUp()`
  runs before every unit/fuzz test AND once at the start of every
  invariant campaign.
* Prefer `vm.expectRevert(<selector or message>)` for negative tests.
  Reserve `expect_test_failure` for cases where the *entire* test must
  fail (not just an inner call); see "Expecting test failure" below.
* When you need to mock, `vm.mockCall` is the cheatcode; look it up with
  `foundry_cheatcodes_manual_search` if you haven't used it before.
* **If `forge_test` reports a build failure, fix the compile error before
  anything else** -- before iterating on test logic or fuzz seeds.

## Writing fuzz tests

A `testFuzz_*(args)` function is fuzzed automatically -- foundry generates
random values for each parameter on every run (default ~256 runs per
test, configured per project in `foundry.toml`). A few things to keep in
mind so the fuzzer actually exercises the property:

* **Constrain inputs at the top.** Random `uint256` will mostly be huge
  garbage. Use `bound(x, lo, hi)` (a `Test` helper) to fold the value
  into `[lo, hi]`, or `vm.assume(cond)` to *discard* runs where the
  precondition fails. `bound` is cheaper than `assume` because it
  doesn't waste a fuzz run; prefer `bound` for numeric ranges and
  reserve `assume` for things you can't easily fold (e.g.,
  `vm.assume(addr != address(0))`).
* **Avoid spurious reverts** in the test body -- if a fuzz test reverts
  because of an unconstrained input (e.g., not enough balance), the run
  is silently discarded and you learn nothing from it. Set up
  preconditions explicitly: mint/approve/deal whatever the body needs.
* **Use `vm.deal(addr, amount)` and `deal(token, addr, amount)`** (the
  forge-std helper) to seed balances rather than transferring from a
  rich account -- much faster and doesn't need a "rich" address to
  exist.
* **Iterating on a fuzz failure uses the `seed` arg of `forge_test`.**
  An unseeded run is a fresh fuzz campaign with no carryover. When a
  fuzz/invariant test fails and you want to *iterate on that specific
  counterexample*, pass the SAME `forge_test(seed="X")` across calls --
  it replays the prior failing inputs first, so you can make monotonic
  progress on the bug. Then, once the seeded run is clean, do ONE more
  `forge_test()` WITHOUT a seed -- **only unseeded runs are eligible to
  stamp the publish gate**.
* **For address fuzz inputs**, almost always `vm.assume(addr !=
  address(0))` (and often `!= address(this)`, `!= precompile addresses`).
  Foundry's fuzzer doesn't avoid these by default.

## Writing invariant tests

An `invariant_*` function is run by foundry's *stateful* fuzzer: it
generates a random sequence of function calls against your targeted
contracts and checks the invariant after every step. This is much more
powerful than `testFuzz_*` (which only fuzzes one call's arguments) but
also much more brittle -- by default the fuzzer will call *every* public
function on *every* deployed contract, which produces nonsense
campaigns. You almost always need a **handler** contract.

### The handler pattern (essentially mandatory)

```solidity
contract Handler is Test {
    Vault vault;
    uint256 public ghostDeposits;   // ghost var the invariant checks against

    constructor(Vault v) { vault = v; }

    function deposit(uint256 amt) external {
        amt = bound(amt, 1, type(uint128).max);   // keep inputs sane
        vault.deposit{value: amt}();
        ghostDeposits += amt;
    }
    // ...one wrapper per operation the fuzzer should exercise...
}

contract VaultInvariant is Test {
    Vault vault; Handler handler;

    function setUp() public {
        vault = new Vault();
        handler = new Handler(vault);
        targetContract(address(handler));   // <-- restricts the fuzzer
    }

    function invariant_TotalSupplyMatchesDeposits() public view {
        assertEq(vault.totalSupply(), handler.ghostDeposits());
    }
}
```

The handler exists for three reasons:

1. **Scope** -- `targetContract(address(handler))` in `setUp()` tells
   the fuzzer to only call functions on the handler. Without this, the
   fuzzer calls everything on every deployed contract and you'll
   spend most of the campaign on reverts and no-ops.
2. **Input shaping** -- use `bound(...)` (preferred) or `vm.assume(...)`
   inside handler functions to keep inputs in valid ranges. With
   `fail_on_revert = false` (the default) reverting calls are silently
   dropped from the sequence, which means an invariant can *pass
   trivially* because every state-violating call reverts. Shape inputs
   so calls succeed.
3. **Ghost variables** -- fields on the handler track state the
   invariant compares against (sum of deposits, max balance seen,
   number of users created, etc.). The invariant reads them via
   `handler.ghostX()` and asserts equality against the contract under
   test.

### Targeting / scoping cheatcodes (call from `setUp()`)

* `targetContract(address)` -- restrict to these contracts. Standard.
* `excludeContract(address)` -- blacklist a specific contract.
* `targetSelector(FuzzSelector{addr: ..., selectors: [...]})` -- restrict
  to specific function selectors on a contract.
* `targetSender(address)` -- pin the set of `msg.sender`s the fuzzer
  rotates through. Default is random EOAs every call, which usually
  produces nothing but `Unauthorized` reverts on access-controlled
  contracts. Add 3–4 fixed senders in `setUp()` and `targetSender` them.

### Initial state ("base case")

Each campaign starts from the post-`setUp()` state. Across the
configured number of `runs` (default 256), every campaign is an
independent fork of that single starting state -- state doesn't leak
between campaigns. Whatever you put in `setUp()` is the world the
fuzzer sees from step 0; pre-seed users / balances / parameters there
when the invariant only makes sense in a non-trivial state, otherwise
the early steps of every campaign are wasted reaching a sensible
configuration.

### Top-level invariant function rules

* `public view` (no mutation, no cheatcodes that mutate). Forge calls
  it after every step -- if it reverts or an `assertEq` fails, the
  campaign is reported failing with the call sequence that triggered it.
* No arguments -- invariants don't take fuzzed inputs at the top level.
  All randomness comes from the handler's call sequence.

### Optional hooks

* `afterInvariant()` -- runs once at the end of each campaign, after
  the final invariant check. Use for finalizing ghost-var bookkeeping
  if needed.

### Configuration knobs (mention them in commentary if you tuned them)

The default `runs = 256, depth = 500` is fine for shallow properties.
If the invariant requires the fuzzer to reach a specific deep state
(e.g., 50+ deposits before a rebalance is triggered), you may need
more depth. You don't directly edit `foundry.toml` from here -- but
flag in your publish commentary if the property looked under-exercised
so the human can bump the budget.

## Expecting test failure (rare)

When you genuinely want a test to fail (because the failure proves
something about the system) you can mark that test via
`expect_test_failure`. Reserve this for cases like:

1. You're asked to demonstrate that an attack/exploit *cannot* occur,
   and the natural formulation is a test that succeeds iff the attack
   succeeds. In that case the test failing is the desired outcome.
2. A toolchain limitation is making a correctly-written test fail and
   you've exhausted alternatives.

In every other case, structure your test so that *passing* corresponds
to the property holding.
